    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2917159723" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2917159723" />
    <a title="Tim Popko" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35864928-tim-popko"><img alt="Tim Popko" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2917159723?book_show_action=true">Mar 31, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim Popko" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim Popko" href="/user/show/35864928-tim-popko">Tim Popko</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2917159723&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2917159723" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12621318978883093056">Queen maker by India Edghill is an expository tale of Michal, David’s first wife, and one of the Bible’s lesser known figures. Although this is Edghill’s first book, it is clear from the onset that she has a strong sense of Biblical themes and philosophies that she wants to imbue as a writer.<br/><br/>Michal tells the entire tale, with a narrative that in some ways feels limited, and at other times had me kept in rapt attention. She was Saul’s daughter, and had wisdom beyond her years even as a child; she</span>
  <span id="freeText12621318978883093056" style="display:none">Queen maker by India Edghill is an expository tale of Michal, David’s first wife, and one of the Bible’s lesser known figures. Although this is Edghill’s first book, it is clear from the onset that she has a strong sense of Biblical themes and philosophies that she wants to imbue as a writer.<br /><br />Michal tells the entire tale, with a narrative that in some ways feels limited, and at other times had me kept in rapt attention. She was Saul’s daughter, and had wisdom beyond her years even as a child; she fell head over heels for the young poetic David, and even helped him save his own life when Saul despised him. As she separated from David, and has a new husband foisted upon her, a growing sense of wrathfulness and ardent feminism seems to take hold - she withholds affection from her husband, and leaves him in scorn for years before she begins to love and understand him.<br /><br />Flash forward ten years, and Michal is reunited with David, a man who has undergone enormous trials and tribulations to become King of Israel, and who wants her as his first queen. Edghill spares no detail in Michal’s narrative; she laments the orderliness of David’s house, and acts suspicious of David’s love towards her. Most tellingly, she passes off David’s royal gifts and insists time and again that she be released to rejoin her farmer husband.<br /><br />Michal’s life is miserable for many years in the palace, but with time she makes female-bonding with concubine Zhurleen and David’s new mistress Bathsheba a focus of her life. All the gossip, and plotting, and Michal’s final scheme to get Solomon onto the throne make for a very unorthodox read - who would suspect that a person in the Bible, married to the love of her life after ten years of separation, in a grand palace with all the time and pleasure in the world, would be someone so calculating, wrathful, and duplicitous? And who would suspect that David, a man with all the world’s pleasures afforded to him, would still need such ego-stroking, and be so vain, or so shortsighted as to sleep with a soldier’s wife and cover up the affair?<br /><br />Taken together, David and Michal seem to epitomize the “power couple” genre. Both will give and withhold affection at will, and both have conflicts with each other and with themselves, that reach Biblical proportions when nearly anyone that comes in touch is now a pawn at their disposal. Edghill’s depiction of David and Michal is not flattering, and it gets downright blasphemous. I look at some of David’s high points “he was a man after God’s own heart”, and wonder deep down, if God is in anyway as flawed as David. On a related note, Michal’s wide range of feelings towards David reveals that loving someone, anyone, may in fact be a learned experience, and one that takes wisdom in and of itself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12621318978883093056" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

