  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3413157386" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3413157386" />
    <a title="Die Muhme Rumpumpel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/93755849-die-muhme-rumpumpel"><img alt="Die Muhme Rumpumpel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551445227p2/93755849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3413157386?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Die Muhme Rumpumpel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Die Muhme Rumpumpel" href="/user/show/93755849-die-muhme-rumpumpel">Die Muhme Rumpumpel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/93755849-die-muhme-rumpumpel?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3413157386" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5017174893717007446">Michal, the younger daughter of Israels first King Saul, falls madly in love with the stunning shepherd David, who soon rises to Sauls friend, Hero of the Country and - finally, Saul&apos;s son-in-law. Sensing that the young man will soon overshine him, the King tries to kill David, but he is warned and flees the land, helped by his freshly wedded wife Michal. The princess is given to another man, a farmer, and slowly learns to appreciate her new life as well as the love of a gentle husband. <br/><br/>Ten year</span>
  <span id="freeText5017174893717007446" style="display:none">Michal, the younger daughter of Israels first King Saul, falls madly in love with the stunning shepherd David, who soon rises to Sauls friend, Hero of the Country and - finally, Saul's son-in-law. Sensing that the young man will soon overshine him, the King tries to kill David, but he is warned and flees the land, helped by his freshly wedded wife Michal. The princess is given to another man, a farmer, and slowly learns to appreciate her new life as well as the love of a gentle husband. <br /><br />Ten years later, David finally claims the throne for himself. He summons Michal, and since she is the former King's only heir, he declares her publicly the love of his life who has finally returned to him. Michal starts to see through Davids charm and decides to stay with her husband, but the King makes it very clear that this is no option. Though he treats her with love and respect mostly, Michal begins to hate David and waits for a chance to get back to him. She befriends the neighbour's girl Bathsheba, with whom David has one of his numerous affairs, and through her she findes the true love of her life: David's and Bathsheba's son Salomon, who calls Michal his "other mother". <br /><br />Michal enjoys the highest possible status in King David's palace - she is granted everything she wishes for, but she asks for little and waits her time - and in David's old age, she manages to finally overpower him by making him declare the son of her heart his heir. <br /><br />***<br /><br />A lot of people were claiming that this was badly written, if it was, I did not notice. What I did notice, however, was the poor proofreading: I do not think I ever read a book so filled with typos! This is disgraceful. <br />While Michal was no perfect character, she was interesting, especially since she saw through David's intrigues early on but was helpless to do anything against him - this felt honest, I suppose something like this might really have happened. I suppose that this "non-action-y" heroine leaves lots of people unsatisfied - we expect women to be more resourceful than this. Yet, I find all these historical fiction of mega-powerful women suspicious: if every other women had been such a power-girl, patriarchy might not have stayed that long, would it? So, seeing a woman who was confined within a role she did not want to play, who could not help or free herself and still endured until she could break her bond to the man who did this to her, very very powerful. Not all strong women are action heroines. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5017174893717007446" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

