    <a title="Amy Lopski" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28672465-amy-lopski"><img alt="Amy Lopski" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392334142p2/28672465.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2859817282?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy Lopski" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy Lopski" href="/user/show/28672465-amy-lopski">Amy Lopski</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2859817282&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2859817282" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5164637601923499184">Horrible. It seems as the author is not a complete believer on the book she loosely wrote her own book on. First of all, back in those days, God was at the front of everyones minds and for Michal to be so “ungodly” being an ISRAELITE and daughter to Saul who before he became a crazy king was friends with prophets so he would have taught his children the fear of the Lord, so Michal full of hate and wanting vengeance shows the author did not do thorough context research and has painted the times o</span>
  <span id="freeText5164637601923499184" style="display:none">Horrible. It seems as the author is not a complete believer on the book she loosely wrote her own book on. First of all, back in those days, God was at the front of everyones minds and for Michal to be so “ungodly” being an ISRAELITE and daughter to Saul who before he became a crazy king was friends with prophets so he would have taught his children the fear of the Lord, so Michal full of hate and wanting vengeance shows the author did not do thorough context research and has painted the times of king David in the worst light possible, as if this was a Philistine kingdom worshipping idols, instead of a God who btw they saw Him split the sea a few stories back... why isn’t God powerful enough to help a simple man become and stay a king? <br />*Jonathans son was a cripple from birth. Not disfigured by accident<br />*king David was a humble man who feared Yahweh<br />*Israelites did not paint their faces like the Egyptians<br />This book made me mad. <br />Madder still that my son spilt tea all over it and now I have to pay for this book to the library and will have to keep it. I get fiction, but this fiction was so loose she should have never based it on biblical characters if she didn’t understand the basis of the true story. There I said it. This has been boiling inside. <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="5164637601923499184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


